{"title_page": "Jeff Fonda", "text_new": "{{orphan|date=May 2017}}\n\n'''Jeff Fonda''' is the Founder and [[CEO]] of [[The Literate Earth Project]], which as of 2017 had opened 15 libraries in [[Uganda]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theliterateearthproject.org/projects/|title=Home|website=The Literate Earth Project|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-10}}</ref> In 2016 he was named to [[International Literacy Association|International Literacy Association's]] 2016 '30-under-30' list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.literacyworldwide.org/docs/default-source/communications/literacy-today/celebrating-the-next-class-30-under-30-2016.pdf|title=International Literacy Association}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.literacyworldwide.org/docs/default-source/press-releases/ila-30-under-30-press-release-16-09-01.pdf?sfvrsn=4|title=International Literacy Association}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/pennsylvania/roxborough/philly-nonprofit-ceo-named-international-30-under-30-list|title=Roxborough Patch}}</ref> He was also named to the [[State University of New York at New Paltz]] alumni '40-under-40' list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newpaltz.edu/alumni/40underforty/profiles/jeff-fonda/|title=40 Under Forty - SUNY New Paltz|website=www.newpaltz.edu|access-date=2017-11-16}}</ref>\n\nJeff graduated from [[State University of New York at New Paltz|SUNY New Paltz]] with a degree in [[International Relations]] in 2010, where was also elected student body vice president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oracle.newpaltz.edu/new-paltz-races-for-literacy-in-uganda/|title=New Paltz Races for Literacy in Uganda \u2013 The New Paltz Oracle|website=oracle.newpaltz.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-16}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newpaltz.ulsterpublishing.com/printer_friendly/11404693|title=Where no cars go|website=newpaltz.ulsterpublishing.com|access-date=2017-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thelittlerebellion.com/index.php/2011/04/the-budget-aftermath-2/|title=The Budget Aftermath|date=2011-04-07|work=The Little Rebellion|access-date=2017-11-16|language=en-US}}</ref> He is currently a Global Masters of Business Administration student at [[Fox School of Business and Management|Temple University's Fox School of Business]] with expected graduation in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessbecause.com/news/mba-entrepreneurs/4649/social-impact-fox-mbas-nonprofit-libraries-schools-uganda|title=Social Impact: Fox MBA\u2019s Nonprofit Opens Up Libraries At Schools In Uganda|work=BusinessBecause|access-date=2017-11-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fonda, Jeff}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-CEO-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{orphan|date=May 2017}}\n\n'''Jeff Fonda''' is the Founder and [[CEO]] of [[The Literate Earth Project]], which as of 2017 had opened 15 libraries in [[Uganda]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theliterateearthproject.org/projects/|title=Home|website=The Literate Earth Project|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-10}}</ref> In 2016 he was named to [[International Literacy Association|International Literacy Association's]] 2016 '30-under-30' list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.literacyworldwide.org/docs/default-source/communications/literacy-today/celebrating-the-next-class-30-under-30-2016.pdf|title=International Literacy Association}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.literacyworldwide.org/docs/default-source/press-releases/ila-30-under-30-press-release-16-09-01.pdf?sfvrsn=4|title=International Literacy Association}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/pennsylvania/roxborough/philly-nonprofit-ceo-named-international-30-under-30-list|title=Roxborough Patch}}</ref> He was also named to the [[State University of New York at New Paltz]] alumni '40-under-40' list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newpaltz.edu/alumni/40underforty/profiles/jeff-fonda/|title=40 Under Forty - SUNY New Paltz|website=www.newpaltz.edu|access-date=2017-11-16}}</ref>\n\nJeff graduated from [[State University of New York at New Paltz|SUNY New Paltz]] with a degree in [[International Relations]] in 2010, where was also elected Student Body Vice President.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oracle.newpaltz.edu/new-paltz-races-for-literacy-in-uganda/|title=New Paltz Races for Literacy in Uganda \u2013 The New Paltz Oracle|website=oracle.newpaltz.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-16}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newpaltz.ulsterpublishing.com/printer_friendly/11404693|title=Where no cars go|website=newpaltz.ulsterpublishing.com|access-date=2017-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thelittlerebellion.com/index.php/2011/04/the-budget-aftermath-2/|title=The Budget Aftermath|date=2011-04-07|work=The Little Rebellion|access-date=2017-11-16|language=en-US}}</ref> He is currently a Global Masters of Business Administration student at [[Fox School of Business and Management|Temple University's Fox School of Business]] with expected graduation in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessbecause.com/news/mba-entrepreneurs/4649/social-impact-fox-mbas-nonprofit-libraries-schools-uganda|title=Social Impact: Fox MBA\u2019s Nonprofit Opens Up Libraries At Schools In Uganda|work=BusinessBecause|access-date=2017-11-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fonda, Jeff}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-CEO-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:replaced: Student Body Vice President \u2192 student body vice president", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Fonda"}
{"title_page": "Anne Stanhope, Countess of Chesterfield", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Anne Seymour, Duchess of Somerset}}\n{{Infobox Person\n| name        = Anne Stanhope, Countess of Chesterfield\n| image       = Anne Stanhope, Countess of Chesterfield in 1840 from NPG.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = by [[Richard James Lane]], in 1840 after [[Alfred d'Orsay|Alfred, Count D'Orsay]]\n| birth_name  = Anne Elizabeth Forester\n| birth_date  = September 7, 1802\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = July 27, 1885\n| death_place = [[Bretby]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   = correspondent\n| occupation  =\n| spouse      = [[George Stanhope, 6th Earl of Chesterfield]]\n| children    = 2; including [[George Stanhope, 7th Earl of Chesterfield|George]]\n| relatives   =[[Selina Bridgeman, Countess of Bradford]] (sister)<br>[[Charles Manners, 4th Duke of Rutland]] (grandfather)<br>[[George Herbert, 5th Earl of Carnarvon]] (grandson)\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]\n|father=[[Cecil Weld-Forester, 1st Baron Forester]]}}\n'''Anne Elizabeth Stanhope (''n\u00e9e'' Weld-Forester), Countess of Chesterfield''' (1802\u20131885) was known as a political confidante.\n\n==Life==\nStanhope was born on 7 September 1802, the eldest daughter of [[Cecil Weld-Forester, 1st Baron Forester]], [[Member of Parliament|M.P.]], and Lady Katherine Manners, the daughter of [[Charles Manners, 4th Duke of Rutland]]. The family home was [[Willey, Shropshire|Willey Park]] in [[Shropshire]].\n \nIn 1830 [[Lord Derby]] proposed to her, but she instead accepted the proposal of [[George Stanhope, 6th Earl of Chesterfield|Lord Chesterfield]]. They had one son and a daughter, Lady Evelyn Stanhope (1834\u20131875), later the first wife of [[Henry Herbert, 4th Earl of Carnarvon]]. Anne Stanhope's husband was considered a wastrel, who spent much of his time asleep in [[Bretby Hall]] and let his lands at [[Bretby]] to go to waste. He died in June 1866, aged 61, and was succeeded by their son, [[George Stanhope, 7th Earl of Chesterfield|George]].  \n\nLike her sister Selina, Countess of Bradford, Anne was an intimate friend of [[Benjamin Disraeli]]. After they had both been widowed Disraeli is said to have proposed to her, but she declined, saying that people over seventy would be foolish to marry. Some of their friends thought that she refused him because she believed that he cared more for her sister.<ref>Pearson, Hesketh.  ''Dizzy: The Life and Personality of Benjamin Disraeli, Earl of Beaconsfield.''  New York:  Harper Collins, 1951, p.243.</ref> Nevertheless, she was Disraeli's confidante, and they exchanged hundreds of letters.<ref name=\"ddd\" />\n\nShe continued to live at Bretby Hall. She died on 27 July 1885, having outlived her son and daughter.<ref name=\"ddd\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-50251|title=Stanhope [n\u00e9e Forester], Anne Elizabeth, countess of Chesterfield (1802\u20131885), political confidante {{!}} Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|website=www.oxforddnb.com|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/50251|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanhope, Anne}}\n[[Category:1802 births]]\n[[Category:1885 deaths]]\n[[Category:British reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:People from Derbyshire (before 1895)]]\n[[Category:British countesses]]\n[[Category:Daughters of barons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Anne Seymour, Duchess of Somerset}}\n{{Infobox Person\n| name        = Anne Stanhope, Countess of Chesterfield\n| image       = Anne Stanhope, Countess of Chesterfield in 1840 from NPG.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = by [[Richard James Lane]], in 1840 after [[Alfred d'Orsay|Alfred, Count D'Orsay]]\n| birth_name  = Anne Elizabeth Forester\n| birth_date  = September 7, 1802\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = July 27, 1885\n| death_place = [[Bretby]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   = correspondent\n| occupation  =\n| spouse      = [[George Stanhope, 6th Earl of Chesterfield]]\n| children    = 2; including [[George Stanhope, 7th Earl of Chesterfield|George]]\n| relatives   =[[Selina Bridgeman, Countess of Bradford]] (sister)<br>[[Charles Manners, 4th Duke of Rutland]] (grandfather)<br>[[George Herbert, 5th Earl of Carnarvon]] (grandson)\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]\n|father=[[Cecil Weld-Forester, 1st Baron Forester]]}}\n'''Anne Elizabeth Stanhope (''n\u00e9e'' Weld-Forester), Countess of Chesterfield''' (1802\u20131885) was known as a political confidante.\n\n==Life==\nStanhope was the eldest daughter of the member of parliament [[Cecil Weld-Forester, 1st Baron Forester]] and Lady Katherine Manners, the daughter of [[Charles Manners, 4th Duke of Rutland]]. She was born on 7 September 1802. The family home was [[Willey Park]] in Shropshire.\n \nIn 1830 [[Lord Derby]] proposed to her, but she instead accepted the proposal of [[George Stanhope, 6th Earl of Chesterfield|Lord Chesterfield]]. They had one son and a daughter, Lady Evelyn Stanhope (1834\u20131875), later the first wife of [[Henry Herbert, 4th Earl of Carnarvon]]. Anne Stanhope's husband was considered a wastrel, who spent much of his time asleep in [[Bretby Hall]] and let his lands at [[Bretby]] to go to waste. He died in June 1866, aged 61, and was succeeded by their son, [[George Stanhope, 7th Earl of Chesterfield|George]].  \n\nLike her sister Selina, Countess of Bradford, Anne was an intimate friend of [[Benjamin Disraeli]]. After they had both been widowed Disraeli is said to have proposed to her,  but she declined on the grounds that people over seventy  would be foolish to marry. Some of their friends thought that she refused him because she believed that he cared more for her sister.<ref>Pearson, Hesketh.  ''Dizzy: The Life and Personality of Benjamin Disraeli, Earl of Beaconsfield.''  New York:  Harper Collins, 1951, p.243.</ref> Nevertheless she was Disraeli's confidante and they exchanged hundreds of letters.<ref name=\"ddd\" />\n\nShe continued to live at Bretby Hall. She died on 27 July 1885 having outlived her son and daughter.<ref name=\"ddd\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-50251|title=Stanhope [n\u00e9e Forester], Anne Elizabeth, countess of Chesterfield (1802\u20131885), political confidante {{!}} Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|website=www.oxforddnb.com|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/50251|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanhope, Anne}}\n[[Category:1802 births]]\n[[Category:1885 deaths]]\n[[Category:British reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:People from Derbyshire (before 1895)]]\n[[Category:British countesses]]\n[[Category:Daughters of barons]]\n", "name_user": "Textorus", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:clarify and cut wordiness", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anne_Stanhope,_Countess_of_Chesterfield"}
{"title_page": "Ramon Schwartz Jr.", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = \n| name=Ramon Schwartz Jr.\n| image name=\n| order = 56th\n| office = Speaker of the South Carolina House of Representatives\n| term_start= December 1980\n| term_end= October 1, 1986\n| preceded= [[Rex L. Carter]]\n| succeeded=[[Robert Sheheen]]\n| state_house1=South Carolina\n| state1=South Carolina\n| district1=68th\n| term_start1= December 1974\n| term_end1= October 1, 1986\n| preceded1= None (district created)\n| succeeded1= [[Joe McElveen]]\n| office2= Member of the [[South Carolina House of Representatives]] from [[Sumter County, South Carolina|Sumter County]]\n| term_start2= December 1968\n| term_end2= December 1974\n| preceded2= [[Henry C. Edens]]\n| succeeded2= None (districts numbered)\n| birth_date={{birth date|1925|5|25}}\n| birth_place=[[Sumter, South Carolina|Sumter]], [[South Carolina]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|2017|6|30|1925|5|25}}\n| death_place=Sumter, South Carolina\n| spouse=Rosa Weinberg\n| profession=\n| alma_mater= {{nowrap|[[University of South Carolina]]}}\n| religion=\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|}}\n\n'''Ramon Schwartz Jr.''' (May 25, 1925 &ndash; June 30, 2017) was an American politician in the state of [[South Carolina]]. He served in the [[South Carolina House of Representatives]] from 1969 to 1987 as a Democrat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=HcVWAAAAYAAJ&q=%22schwartz,+ramon+jr.%22+1925&dq=%22schwartz,+ramon+jr.%22+1925&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tzKuVP_EEcmzogTirIHIBw&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAw|title=South Carolina Legislative Manual|first=South Carolina General|last=Assembly|date=4 July 1975|publisher=General Assembly of South Carolina.|accessdate=4 July 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=B1d3AAAAMAAJ&q=%22schwartz,+ramon+jr.%22+1925&dq=%22schwartz,+ramon+jr.%22+1925&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tzKuVP_EEcmzogTirIHIBw&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAQ|title=American Legislative Leaders in the South, 1911-1994|first1=James Roger|last1=Sharp|first2=Nancy Weatherly|last2=Sharp|date=1 January 1999|publisher=Greenwood Press|accessdate=4 July 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref> Schwartz was an attorney and lived in [[Sumter, South Carolina]]. He served as speaker pro tempore prior to his election to the position of Speaker of the House in 1980, in which he served until his retirement in 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1979&dat=19860527&id=WaQiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gK0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=4574,5166678|title=The Sumter Daily Item - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref> He was an alumnus of the [[University of South Carolina]], where he was a member of the [[Euphradian Society]] and also the institution's first-ever student body vice president. Additionally, Schwartz is a veteran of [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scstatehouse.gov/cgi-bin/query.exe?first=DOC&querytext=report&category=Legislation&session=ALL&conid=0&result_pos=18850&keyval=1164596|title=Query - South Carolina Legislature Online|website=www.scstatehouse.gov|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1979&dat=19801119&id=ZWIlAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qKoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2522,3042588|title=The Sumter Daily Item - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref><ref>http://www.goupstate.com/assets/pdf/SJ16730529.PDF</ref> He died in Sumter in 2017 at the age of 92.<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theitem.com/stories/ramon-schwartz-jr-has-died,291648|title=Ramon Schwartz Jr. has died|website=theitem.com|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schwartz, Ramon}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Sumter, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:University of South Carolina alumni]]\n[[Category:South Carolina lawyers]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the South Carolina House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the South Carolina House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from South Carolina]]\n\n\n{{SouthCarolina-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = \n| name=Ramon Schwartz Jr.\n| image name=\n| order = 56th\n| office = Speaker of the South Carolina House of Representatives\n| term_start= December 1980\n| term_end= October 1, 1986\n| preceded= [[Rex L. Carter]]\n| succeeded=[[Robert Sheheen]]\n| state_house1=South Carolina\n| state1=South Carolina\n| district1=68th\n| term_start1= December 1974\n| term_end1= October 1, 1986\n| preceded1= None (district created)\n| succeeded1= [[Joe McElveen]]\n| office2= Member of the [[South Carolina House of Representatives]] from [[Sumter County, South Carolina|Sumter County]]\n| term_start2= December 1968\n| term_end2= December 1974\n| preceded2= [[Henry C. Edens]]\n| succeeded2= None (districts numbered)\n| birth_date={{birth date|1925|5|25}}\n| birth_place=[[Sumter, South Carolina|Sumter]], [[South Carolina]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|2017|6|30|1925|5|25}}\n| death_place=Sumter, South Carolina\n| spouse=Rosa Weinberg\n| profession=\n| alma_mater= {{nowrap|[[University of South Carolina]]}}\n| religion=\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|}}\n\n'''Ramon Schwartz Jr.''' (May 25, 1925 &ndash; June 30, 2017) was an American politician in the state of [[South Carolina]]. He served in the [[South Carolina House of Representatives]] from 1969 to 1987 as a Democrat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=HcVWAAAAYAAJ&q=%22schwartz,+ramon+jr.%22+1925&dq=%22schwartz,+ramon+jr.%22+1925&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tzKuVP_EEcmzogTirIHIBw&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAw|title=South Carolina Legislative Manual|first=South Carolina General|last=Assembly|date=4 July 1975|publisher=General Assembly of South Carolina.|accessdate=4 July 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=B1d3AAAAMAAJ&q=%22schwartz,+ramon+jr.%22+1925&dq=%22schwartz,+ramon+jr.%22+1925&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tzKuVP_EEcmzogTirIHIBw&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAQ|title=American Legislative Leaders in the South, 1911-1994|first1=James Roger|last1=Sharp|first2=Nancy Weatherly|last2=Sharp|date=1 January 1999|publisher=Greenwood Press|accessdate=4 July 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref> Schwartz was an attorney and lived in [[Sumter, South Carolina]]. He served as speaker pro tempore prior to his election to the position of Speaker of the House in 1980, in which he served until his retirement in 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1979&dat=19860527&id=WaQiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gK0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=4574,5166678|title=The Sumter Daily Item - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref> He was an alumnus of the [[University of South Carolina]], where he was a member of the [[Euphradian Society]] and also the institution's first-ever Student Body Vice President. Additionally, Schwartz is a veteran of [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scstatehouse.gov/cgi-bin/query.exe?first=DOC&querytext=report&category=Legislation&session=ALL&conid=0&result_pos=18850&keyval=1164596|title=Query - South Carolina Legislature Online|website=www.scstatehouse.gov|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1979&dat=19801119&id=ZWIlAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qKoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2522,3042588|title=The Sumter Daily Item - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref><ref>http://www.goupstate.com/assets/pdf/SJ16730529.PDF</ref> He died in Sumter in 2017 at the age of 92.<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theitem.com/stories/ramon-schwartz-jr-has-died,291648|title=Ramon Schwartz Jr. has died|website=theitem.com|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schwartz, Ramon}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Cate