{"title_page": "Mairangi Bay", "text_new": "{{For|the container ship|MV Mairangi Bay}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox New Zealand suburbs\n| name           = Mairangi Bay\n| image          = \n| caption1       = \n| city1          = [[Auckland Council]]\n| city2          =\n| ward           =\n| established    =\n| coordinates    = {{coord|36|44|19|S|174|44|54|E|type:landmark_region:NZ|display=it}}\n| area           =173.13 <!-- approximately -->\n| population     = 5,346\n| popdate        = 2013\n| trainstations  =\n| ferryterminals =\n| airports       =\n| hospitals      =\n| north          = [[Murrays Bay]]\n| northeast      = ([[Hauraki Gulf]])\n| east           = ([[Hauraki Gulf]])\n| southeast      = [[Campbells Bay]]\n| south          = [[Campbells Bay]]\n| southwest      = [[Sunset North]]\n| west           = [[Windsor Park, New Zealand|Windsor Park]]\n| northwest      = [[Pinehill, New Zealand|Pinehill]]\n| map            =\n| caption2       =\n}}\n[[File:Beach Wood.jpg|thumb|A log on Mairangi Bay beach]]\n[[File:Waves on the Coast at Mairangi Bay.jpg|thumb|Waves crash onto the Mairangi Bay coast.]]\n\n'''Mairangi Bay''' is a coastal suburb of [[North Shore, Auckland]], located in the northern North Island of [[New Zealand]], on the south-east-facing peninsula forming the northern side of the [[Waitemat\u0101 Harbour]]. Mairangi Bay came under the local governance of the [[North Shore, New Zealand|North Shore City Council]] until subsumed into the [[Auckland Council]] in 2010. The population was 5,346 in the [[2013 New Zealand census|2013 census]], an increase of 69 from 2006.<ref>{{NZ Quickstats2013|13234}}</ref>\n\nThe Bay's beach itself has, along with adjacent Murrays and [[Campbells Bay]]s, undergone civil works projects since 2004 to improve stormwater management.<ref>\n[http://nscc.govt.nz/your_council/agendas_minutes/works-environment/wks-agd-031202.pdf Works & Environment Committee, North Shore City Council, 3 December 2002] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928100004/http://nscc.govt.nz/your_council/agendas_minutes/works-environment/wks-agd-031202.pdf |date=28 September 2007 }}\n</ref>\n\n==Education==\nMairangi Bay School and St John's School are coeducational contributing primary (years 1-6) schools with [[Socio-Economic Decile|decile rating]]s of 10 and rolls of 403<ref>{{TKI|1343|Mairangi Bay School}}</ref> and 315,<ref>{{TKI|1492|St Johns School}}</ref> respectively. Mairangi Bay School was founded in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edtech.co.nz/Store/6/27/rm/Mairangi%Bay%Case%Study%2006.pdf |format=PDF |title=Mairangi Bay Case Study 2 |publisher=Edtech Limited |accessdate=2009-01-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014010506/http://edtech.co.nz/Store/6/27/rm/Mairangi%20Bay%20Case%20Study%202006.pdf |archivedate=14 October 2008 }}</ref> St John's is a state integrated Catholic School, which was founded in 1961.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stjohnsmairangibay.school.nz/schoolhistory.htm |title=A History of Development |publisher=St John's School |accessdate=2009-01-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014011416/http://www.stjohnsmairangibay.school.nz/schoolhistory.htm |archivedate=14 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[Rangitoto College]] is a large secondary school in Windsor Park, to the west of Mairangi Bay.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mairangibay.school.nz/ Mairangi Bay School website]\n* [http://www.stjohnsmairangibay.school.nz/ St Johns School website]\n* [https://kura.aucklandlibraries.govt.nz/digital/collection/photos/search/searchterm/Mairangi%20Bay/field/title/ Photographs of Mairangi Bay] held in [[Auckland Libraries|Auckland Libraries']] heritage collections.\n\n\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Auckland]]\n[[Category:North Shore, New Zealand]]\n\n\n{{Auckland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|the container ship|MV Mairangi Bay}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox New Zealand suburbs\n| name           = Mairangi Bay\n| image          = \n| caption1       = \n| city1          = [[Auckland Council]]\n| city2          =\n| ward           =\n| established    =\n| coordinates    = {{coord|36|44|19|S|174|44|54|E|type:landmark_region:NZ|display=it}}\n| area           =173.13 <!-- approximately -->\n| population     = 5,346\n| popdate        = 2013\n| trainstations  =\n| ferryterminals =\n| airports       =\n| hospitals      =\n| north          = [[Murrays Bay]]\n| northeast      = ([[Hauraki Gulf]])\n| east           = ([[Hauraki Gulf]])\n| southeast      = [[Campbells Bay]]\n| south          = [[Campbells Bay]]\n| southwest      = [[Sunset North]]\n| west           = [[Windsor Park, New Zealand|Windsor Park]]\n| northwest      = [[Pinehill, New Zealand|Pinehill]]\n| map            =\n| caption2       =\n}}\n[[File:Beach Wood.jpg|thumb|A log on Mairangi Bay beach]]\n[[File:Waves on the Coast at Mairangi Bay.jpg|thumb|Waves crash onto the Mairangi Bay coast.]]\n\n'''Mairangi Bay''' is a coastal suburb of [[North Shore, Auckland]], located in the northern North Island of [[New Zealand]], on the south-east-facing peninsula forming the northern side of the [[Waitemat\u0101 Harbour]]. Mairangi Bay came under the local governance of the [[North Shore, New Zealand|North Shore City Council]] until subsumed into the [[Auckland Council]] in 2010. The population was 5,346 in the [[2013 New Zealand census|2013 census]], an increase of 69 from 2006.<ref>{{NZ Quickstats2013|13234}}</ref>\n\nThe Bay's beach itself has, along with adjacent Murrays and [[Campbells Bay]]s, undergone civil works projects since 2004 to improve stormwater management.<ref>\n[http://nscc.govt.nz/your_council/agendas_minutes/works-environment/wks-agd-031202.pdf Works & Environment Committee, North Shore City Council, 3 December 2002] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928100004/http://nscc.govt.nz/your_council/agendas_minutes/works-environment/wks-agd-031202.pdf |date=28 September 2007 }}\n</ref>\n\n==Education==\nMairangi Bay School and St John's School are coeducational contributing primary (years 1-6) schools with [[Socio-Economic Decile|decile rating]]s of 10 and rolls of 403<ref>{{TKI|1343|Mairangi Bay School}}</ref> and 315,<ref>{{TKI|1492|St Johns School}}</ref> respectively. Mairangi Bay School was founded in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edtech.co.nz/Store/6/27/rm/Mairangi%Bay%Case%Study%2006.pdf |format=PDF |title=Mairangi Bay Case Study 2 |publisher=Edtech Limited |accessdate=2009-01-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014010506/http://edtech.co.nz/Store/6/27/rm/Mairangi%20Bay%20Case%20Study%202006.pdf |archivedate=14 October 2008 }}</ref> St John's is a state integrated Catholic School, which was founded in 1961.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stjohnsmairangibay.school.nz/schoolhistory.htm |title=A History of Development |publisher=St John's School |accessdate=2009-01-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014011416/http://www.stjohnsmairangibay.school.nz/schoolhistory.htm |archivedate=14 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[Rangitoto College]] is a large secondary school in Windsor Park, to the west of Mairangi Bay.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mairangibay.school.nz/ Mairangi Bay School website]\n* [http://www.stjohnsmairangibay.school.nz/ St Johns School website]\n* [https://kura.aucklandlibraries.govt.nz/digital/?p=q&collection=p20062coll1&search=mairangi%20bay&field=title&mode=all&conn= Photographs of Mairangi Bay] held in [[Auckland Libraries|Auckland Libraries']] heritage collections.\n\n\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Auckland]]\n[[Category:North Shore, New Zealand]]\n\n\n{{Auckland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Agh47", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:updated photographs link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.o